140
00:15:06,774 --> 00:15:09,498
See, at four o'clock in the afternoon.

141
00:15:10,378 --> 00:15:10,678
Not yet.

142
00:15:11,198 --> 00:15:12,039
No, it's near enough.

143
00:15:12,480 --> 00:15:13,802
Okay, it's getting close.

144
00:15:13,861 --> 00:15:14,121
Okay.

145
00:15:16,024 --> 00:15:16,364
Relax.

146
00:15:16,703 --> 00:15:19,326
So, this intention for coffee comes up, you see.

147
00:15:19,366 --> 00:15:23,169
Now, normally speaking, there's an immediate identification with it.

148
00:15:23,610 --> 00:15:24,331
I want coffee.

149
00:15:24,371 --> 00:15:26,113
The I comes in at that point.

150
00:15:26,673 --> 00:15:32,438
And once the I comes in, it's impossible to stop the next moment of willing.

151
00:15:33,379 --> 00:15:33,580
See?

152
00:15:33,860 --> 00:15:35,221
So, it's coffee.

153
00:15:35,241 --> 00:15:35,381
Coffee.

154
00:15:35,716 --> 00:15:35,995
Right?

155
00:15:36,115 --> 00:15:36,697
Feeling coffee.

156
00:15:37,096 --> 00:15:37,418
Want.

157
00:15:38,259 --> 00:15:38,359
I.

158
00:15:39,379 --> 00:15:39,580
Get.

159
00:15:40,760 --> 00:15:41,341
That's how it goes.

160
00:15:42,202 --> 00:15:44,825
Now, in our language, we say, I want coffee.

161
00:15:44,885 --> 00:15:45,306
But it's not.

162
00:15:45,365 --> 00:15:46,466
It's coffee want I.

163
00:15:46,706 --> 00:15:47,467
That's the process.

164
00:15:48,188 --> 00:15:51,251
And because it's coffee want I, you can stop it at the want.

165
00:15:52,052 --> 00:15:53,654
And you don't have to identify with it.

166
00:15:54,716 --> 00:15:54,855
See?

167
00:15:55,537 --> 00:16:01,863
And in not identifying with it, means you don't collapse into, you don't become the desire.

168
00:16:01,883 --> 00:16:05,486
And that moment gives you a moment to say to yourself, well, should I, should I not?

169
00:16:06,174 --> 00:16:11,240
And if you say no, and it's a strong desire, then you have to sort of stay with it, right?

170
00:16:11,559 --> 00:16:15,764
And wait for this pain, this suffering to give way.

171
00:16:15,783 --> 00:16:18,485
You see, you get this tremendous urge for coffee, just to wait.

172
00:16:19,147 --> 00:16:26,874
And as it passes away, what's actually disappearing, what's actually being undermined is the force of that habit.

173
00:16:26,894 --> 00:16:27,375
See?

174
00:16:27,394 --> 00:16:32,298
So the next time that intention comes up for coffee, it's not so great.

175
00:16:33,299 --> 00:16:34,681
It's not so grasping.

176
00:16:35,101 --> 00:16:35,322
See?

177
00:16:35,690 --> 00:16:37,110
and eventually it'll die out.

178
00:16:38,312 --> 00:16:56,931
Now if we did that as a constant throughout our lives, every time we saw, first of all, to be awake to see an intention, secondly to have the patience when we see there's an unwholesome intention to die away, you see, very quickly you change your habits.

179
00:16:56,951 --> 00:17:04,178
And of course in the opposite, every time you see an intention which you come as wholesome, and there's this negativity saying,

180
00:17:04,444 --> 00:17:05,987
No, I don't want to do that.

181
00:17:06,326 --> 00:17:13,575
But you actually do it, you see, then you're producing a habit which is taking you into wholesomeness.

182
00:17:13,595 --> 00:17:14,015
That's all.

183
00:17:14,055 --> 00:17:17,999
Now, that is practice in daily life in a very simple way.

184
00:17:18,480 --> 00:17:18,660
See?

185
00:17:19,160 --> 00:17:27,028
Now, what we do is, the coffee comes up, you see, and you say, no, no, and you suffer and you suffer and you suffer and then it finally gives away and you think, great, I gave up coffee, you see.

186
00:17:27,869 --> 00:17:31,192
And then you're a bit anxious, you're a bit depressed, you see.

187
00:17:31,492 --> 00:17:33,134
Coffee comes up, whoop, you have coffee.

188
00:17:33,689 --> 00:17:38,535
So one minute we're letting go, and the next minute we're finding it again.

189
00:17:39,276 --> 00:17:42,759
And that's why it takes so long to become liberated.

190
00:17:43,881 --> 00:17:52,612
But if we were actually fierce in our intention and never gave way, then we'd very quickly change ourselves.

191
00:17:54,213 --> 00:17:57,136
And that's the core practice.

192
00:17:58,959 --> 00:17:59,980
And that's the core practice.

193
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:02,282
It doesn't matter whether you're a lay person or a monastic.

194
00:18:02,384 --> 00:18:03,644
That's the core practice.

195
00:18:03,794 --> 00:18:31,000
right as right speech right action and right livelihood so take livelihood for instance whatever your livelihood is you see unless it's obviously a model you know I don't know arms and trafficking humans that's pretty model so if you're not doing that you're all right so most people have jobs which are in themselves wholesome

196
00:18:31,417 --> 00:18:35,122
What turns it into a spiritual practice is your attitude to the job.

197
00:18:35,942 --> 00:18:42,369
If you see yourself doing work which is a service to others, that's an immediate act of generosity.

198
00:18:43,771 --> 00:18:45,614
Whether you want to or not is immaterial.

199
00:18:47,256 --> 00:19:00,530
It's the fact that you've now intended your work to be a service to others, and of course you include yourself, others and yourself, but mainly your intention is to be of service to others in whatever way you can.

200
00:19:00,932 --> 00:19:30,686
immediately you see whether whether you like it or not you're developing a beautiful attitude and at first it may you may be still stuck with the effects of an old attitude of being grumpy of not wanting to do the work of hating this and hating that you see but as those die away that sense of service begins to resonate in the heart and that's where you get your joy and then then your then your life work becomes a joy no matter what it is whether it's sweeping the streets or

201
00:19:31,055 --> 00:19:40,184
being a nurse or being an astrophysicist, it doesn't really matter, because it's your intention as to why you're doing it, and that becomes right livelihood.

202
00:19:42,906 --> 00:19:55,019
And in ordinary daily life, just washing the pots, you see, washing the pots, you know, I mean, that becomes a practice in itself, right, to actually just put, to turn it into a mindfulness exercise.

203
00:19:55,590 --> 00:20:00,756
And then every time you wash the pots, you can see your mindfulness increasing, you see.

204
00:20:01,196 --> 00:20:05,161
And then you start looking for a job washing pots.

205
00:20:05,381 --> 00:20:06,942
You see, it's such a wonderful practice.

206
00:20:09,384 --> 00:20:10,546
Right speech, you see.

207
00:20:13,068 --> 00:20:16,412
The Buddha talks about kindly speech, right?

208
00:20:16,711 --> 00:20:22,357
To make sure that when you're talking to somebody, it's always coming from some sort of heart of kindness.

209
00:20:22,377 --> 00:20:23,538
It's honest, right?

210
00:20:23,974 --> 00:20:28,622
And the third one, which I think is particularly important, that is at a suitable time.

211
00:20:30,724 --> 00:20:32,467
You don't put your foot in it.

212
00:20:32,527 --> 00:20:40,679
You're actually saying that you might want to say something kindly and you might want to say something honest, but it might not be the right time.

213
00:20:40,999 --> 00:20:43,202
You have to be careful when you say things.

214
00:20:43,623 --> 00:20:51,374
So if you take those three little guidelines, then you're careful in what you say, in what you speak.

215
00:20:51,755 --> 00:20:53,356
It's probably...

216
00:20:53,859 --> 00:20:59,345
The hardest of all these training rules is right speech, because we're always talking.

217
00:21:01,826 --> 00:21:17,701
So you can see that every moment in our lives, from a spiritual point of view, offers this opportunity to bring awareness, to bring goodness, to bring virtue, and naturally, naturally, so you have to work at it, the joy arises.

218
00:21:21,826 --> 00:21:23,326
Now that's the positive bit.

219
00:21:23,694 --> 00:21:32,183
The negative side is, of course, that you have to also work with stuff that comes up, the anxieties, the depressions and whatnot.

220
00:21:32,203 --> 00:21:48,940
And slowly, by finding this position of being able to bear with them, being patient with them, allowing them to manifest at the right time, so that you're no longer hijacked by your emotional states, they no longer govern your life.

221
00:21:49,381 --> 00:21:50,461
See, that's a liberation.

222
00:21:52,618 --> 00:22:02,270
And also not getting that attitude of being against them, fighting them, being frustrated by them, wanting them to go.

223
00:22:02,330 --> 00:22:05,575
You're immediately in conflict.

224
00:22:05,634 --> 00:22:13,743
If you feel a little anxiety and you want it to go, you're in conflict with it, you're creating even more disturbance.

225
00:22:13,763 --> 00:22:20,132
So when we have these negative states, to actually find the space and time to let them express themselves.

226
00:22:21,473 --> 00:22:22,575
And in so doing,

227
00:22:22,825 --> 00:22:51,903
you're allowing that turbulence to die out but also developing an attitude of not being affected by them so that you can carry on your daily life no matter what mental state that happens to arise and remember we were talking about it this morning that when something negative comes you can always park it like a car which is not the same as suppressing suppressing is you push it away with anger

228
00:22:52,238 --> 00:23:20,067
or with fear but just by putting it to the side and then putting your whole attention on what you're doing then as it were you're building up another mental state to the side of it which is joyful and then you find some time in the day or in the week where you can go back to this mental state and let it manifest and that's how you sort of work with negative mental states

229
00:23:22,022 --> 00:23:30,231
So from negative mental states you're bearing them when you can so that they are dying out.

230
00:23:30,251 --> 00:23:42,705
And you're being skillful in the sense that you're not being governed by them, overtaken by them, by putting your attention, by training yourself to put your attention in what is positive and wholesome.

231
00:23:43,727 --> 00:23:49,953
And on the positive side, whenever you see something wholesome or where you want yourself to develop,

232
00:23:50,338 --> 00:23:53,142
you put your whole attention and effort into that area.

233
00:23:54,663 --> 00:23:58,446
Very slowly you move across from darkness to light.

234
00:23:58,467 --> 00:24:00,528
Easy-weezy-peasy.

235
00:24:02,329 --> 00:24:13,240
And when we fail, you see, when we go back to old habits, when you find yourself going down again, you see, so at some point you have to bump, you have to stop, you see.

236
00:24:13,882 --> 00:24:18,445
And then you have to pick yourself up, dust yourself off, and start all over again.

237
00:24:18,465 --> 00:24:19,366
That's it.

238
00:24:19,386 --> 00:24:19,586
And

239
00:24:19,769 --> 00:24:25,478
Frankly, most of our spiritual lives is picking ourselves up, dusting ourselves off and starting all over again.

240
00:24:25,979 --> 00:24:26,339
That's it.

241
00:24:26,740 --> 00:24:27,441
Just very slowly.

242
00:24:28,041 --> 00:24:28,743
Resilience.

243
00:24:29,084 --> 00:24:30,105
Resilience, you see.

244
00:24:31,086 --> 00:24:32,769
Continual effort.

245
00:24:33,852 --> 00:24:34,452
Very slowly.

246
00:24:38,960 --> 00:24:45,871
And that's really basically how we bring the Dhamma into our lives.

247
00:24:45,891 --> 00:24:46,231
So,

248
00:24:46,583 --> 00:24:50,807
There's no mysticism about Buddhist practice.

249
00:24:51,409 --> 00:25:02,080
It really is about developing the good heart, letting go of the heart which is full of horror and misery, and developing the good heart.

250
00:25:03,102 --> 00:25:16,336
And as we're doing that, as we're doing that, you see, there's a natural separation of this awareness, this consciousness,

251
00:25:16,891 --> 00:25:26,584
There's a natural bringing, there's a natural elevation, a movement of this consciousness out of the psycho-physical organism.

252
00:25:29,167 --> 00:25:34,714
Out of emotions, out of the body, out of mind, meaning thoughts and images.

253
00:25:35,636 --> 00:25:39,521
And as it pulls itself out, it comes to recognize its own true nature.

254
00:25:41,003 --> 00:25:46,070
And it's the slow recognition of this consciousness, of this awareness,

255
00:25:46,642 --> 00:25:57,012
that is the spiritual part of your practice, the real spiritual part, because this is what doesn't belong to the earth, it doesn't belong to nature, it's something other than.

256
00:25:58,253 --> 00:26:11,647
And as it gathers its own inner understanding, you see, it now goes back into this psychophysical organism and into the world in order to spread its understanding.

257
00:26:13,470 --> 00:26:15,551
So, when you're sitting in meditation,

258
00:26:15,885 --> 00:26:22,732
you're displacing your attention into an observation post.

259
00:26:22,752 --> 00:26:24,334
It's like a crow's nest on a ship.

260
00:26:24,374 --> 00:26:27,517
You know the bit where the sailor climbs up to see if he can see the land?

261
00:26:28,798 --> 00:26:29,699
So he's up there, you see.

262
00:26:30,099 --> 00:26:36,986
You've discovered this place of the one who knows, the observer, the feeler.

263
00:26:37,527 --> 00:26:43,092
So this is a special place from which you can observe the body with its feelings.

264
00:26:44,911 --> 00:27:14,698
the heart with its emotional states the mind with its thoughts and images the process of desire which is where the problem lies and from that state you see whether we are aware of it or not really recognizing it or not this consciousness has been displaced it's relocated somewhere and in that relocation it's discovering a new identity

265
00:27:15,741 --> 00:27:19,586
So this identity is the observer, the feeler, the knower.

266
00:27:19,606 --> 00:27:23,353
It's still false because there's still somebody there.

267
00:27:23,553 --> 00:27:24,554
It's not the end product.

268
00:27:25,015 --> 00:27:34,848
But it's a place where we can observe the whole process as to how we create happiness or unhappiness for ourselves.

269
00:27:35,009 --> 00:27:42,940
And then slowly but surely, as that becomes more and more obvious to us, then we'll want to stay there more.

270
00:27:43,942 --> 00:27:45,663
You'll want to stay in that peacefulness

271
00:27:46,690 --> 00:27:59,405
And what we discover is that whatever happiness is, it's a difficult one, whatever happiness is, real happiness, true, unchanging, everlasting happiness, is not an emotion.

272
00:28:02,028 --> 00:28:07,415
So that sort of discovery, you see, leads us to a different place.

273
